description: I am just "testing the waters" so to speak. I somehow managed to talk myself into what may not have been my brightest idea ever and bought a couple boats. One is a 1963 27' and the other is a 1964 28' parts boat. They both came from a buddy of mine who has invested a ton of money into the '63. That has two rebuilt 283's and a lot of fresh work in it. The '64 is probably a parts boat. I have a little more than $3K invested in them and would just like to get out of it at this point. My knowledge of boats is limited, but I do know that these old classics are gorgeous and extremely valuable when done right. The '63 has been done perfectly up to this point (with pretty much everything to go with it for finishing the project). It has already had about $21K invested to get it to where it currently is at and yes, I can come up with receipts to prove that. So, like I said...let's see what kind of interest there may be. I am absolutely okay with the barter system also. Cars, trucks, tractors, motorcycles, tools and equipment, hunting "implements", jewelry, old coins, gold...pretty much anything smaller than these two boats. description: I have spent the last two years restoring this boat, we absolutely love it but quickly realized its too small for our family. We put it in the water this past June for the first time and took it to Vancouver Island for a family fishing trip, it was trailered 500 miles round trip, and we ran it every day for the 5 days our fishing licenses were good. It has run awesome every time we've had it out. It has a Mercruiser 120hp engine with Alpha 1 outdrive and will cruse at 25mph, fully loaded with fishing gear and fuel she'll just hit 30mph at WOT. It rides very well for its age and size, we've been caught in some nasty weather and the high hull sides makes it feel very safe. There was no hour meter so engine hours are unknown, we have put 35hrs on the boat since we first put it in this June.  We have used this boat all summer to fish and crab so there are some minor scuffs here and there from normal usage, the engine has developed an oil leak near the transom and the trim gauge sender has gone out but that's it. I work in the marine industry and what I don't have experience in I was able to have professionals help with. I have well over $10,000 in hardware, electronics and paint in this restoration and well over 1000 man hours of work done. I initially was building this boat to last my wife and I for many years but we found out we really like fishing with the rest of the family and our dogs and there just isn't anywhere near enough room for that in this boat. All reasonable offers considered, no trades. As of June this year: -New transom and floor (stringers are fiberglass) -Entire boat has been painted with Interlux Marine Paint systems. - One heavy epoxy barrier coat followed by 4 coats of primer followed by 4 coats of blue on the hull, two coats of white on top and 4 coats of Interlux Speed Coat hard bottom paint. -All railing on the boat is new and stainless, stainless ratchet mount for antenna as well -All wiring has been replaced with marine grade tinned wire -Dual marine grade batteries -New battery switch, bilge pump and switch, wiper motor, gauges, dash switches, LED navigation lights, and LED interior lights -BlueSea Systems circuit breaker panel for downriggers -Standard Horizon VHF radio -Refurbished Alpha Gen 1 transom assembly with new bellows, seals, gimbal bearing and stainless steel swivel pin (a very common leak point) -Brand new SEI outdrive with new Cobra Fin plaining fin, new trim rams, lines and pump -Engine has new manifold and exhaust elbow -Fresh tune up and carb rebuild, also has been converted to Pertronix electronic ignition (no points) -Brand new hoses and belts -Engine has fresh water cooling with brand new Seakamp heat exchanger -New marine grade starter -4 stroke 7hp Honda kicker with fresh tune up oil and water pump -Scotty electric downriggers with swivel bases, were tuned up at LFS marine in Bellingham and re-spooled with stainless wire. -Garmin Echomap 74dv, bought new in March 2016 -1996 Calkins galvanized trailer -All new bearing and seals with Speedi sleeves and stainless bearing buddies -All new LED taillights, marker lights and wire harness -Brand new galvanized wheels and tires -Brand new winch and strap Email, Call or Text 360 Four,Two,Zero 7008, please leave a message
title: Restored 1975 Seaswirl Rouge

description: PAU HANA SPECS Tollycraft 34' Flybridge Sedan, 1975, with twin gas 350 Chevy engines by Mercruiser, heat exchanger cooled.  Beam 12'3", Draft 2'7", displacement 12,000 lbs.  Fiberglass construction and kept under cover.  Two aluminum fuel tanks carrying a total of 190 gallons new in 2009.  One plastic fresh water tank of 75 gallons.   Galley with sink, refrigerator and microwave.  Head with basin, shower and Monomatic  head.  Sleeps six total.  Fishing cockpit is fitted with two downriggers, pole holders, and pole storage rack. As well as davit for pulling crab pots.  This boat has been parked in covered slips for most of it's life and so still has a very good finish on the original gelcoat. She has an FM stereo radio, both FM and AM reception with speakers above and in the main cabin.  Her bridge is the principle control station and is fitted with a Standard Horizon C590 Chart plotter with C-Map card for the NorthWest and a fishfinder attachment that can share the screen or take over all 12" of the display if desired.  She is equipped with a Standard Horizon VHF DSC  Radiotelephone that takes the GPS position from the Chartplotter/fishfinder.  She has both explosive gas sensor alarms in the engineroom and the tank compartment as well as a Co alarm in the Fwd cabin.  She is equipped with three fire extinguishers and two automatic bilge pumps.  She has a class A EPIRB mounted on the after bridge railing as well as the required distress flares and life jackets for six adults and two children.  We enjoy our boat and look forward to moving up to a larger one soon, and we hope to make this one available to someone who will have as much fun with her as we have over the past four years.  If you are interested to see PAU HANA, do contact us by replying to this ad, or better yet, call me at my cel number listed in the ad heading above.  I hope we'll hear from you soon.
title: 34' Tolly Flybridge Sedan
